## Summary of Key Findings

| Aspect                                | Findings                                                                                   |
|-------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Tax Cut Magnitude                    | Middle-class filers ($15,000-$100,000 AGI) received 15%-26% average tax cuts, largest among all groups. |
| Economic Mobility                   | Upward mobility increased, with fewer filers in the lowest income bracket and more in higher brackets. |
| Tax Burden Distribution             | Higher-income earners paid a larger share of total income taxes post-TCJA, indicating increased progressivity. |
| Child Tax Credit and Standard Deduction | Both were doubled, benefiting over 22 million families and simplifying filing for millions. |
| Job and Wage Growth                  | TCJA associated with higher take-home pay and job creation for middle-class workers.       |
| Political Claims vs. Data            | Democratic claims of middle-class tax increases contradicted by IRS data and independent analyses. |

---

## Conclusion

Based on a thorough review of IRS data and multiple analyses from reputable sources, it is clear that the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 significantly benefited the middle class more than any other income group in terms of percentage tax reductions. Middle- and working-class Americans experienced tax cuts ranging from 15% to over 26%, with the largest benefits seen in households earning between $15,000 and $100,000 annually.

Furthermore, the tax reform contributed to upward economic mobility, increased take-home pay, and a more progressive tax burden distribution, with higher-income earners paying a larger share of total income taxes after the reform.

While political rhetoric often painted the TCJA as a giveaway to the wealthy at the expense of the middle class, the empirical data does not support this narrative. Instead, the evidence indicates that the middle class saw substantial tax relief and economic benefits following the implementation of the Trump tax cuts.

